The financial break-even quantity refers to the number of units that the company should produce to achieve a net present value (NPV) which is exactly zero. 
This can be solved using the formula:

$$\begin{aligned}
Q&=\dfrac{\text{FC + OCF}}{\text{P-v}}
\end{aligned}$$

where

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{FC}&=\text{Fixed cost}\\
\text{OFC}&=\text{Operating cashflow}\\
\text{P}&=\text{Price per unit}\\
v&=\text{variable cost per unit}
\end{aligned}$$

Take note that in the given values, the value for $P$ is missing. To solve this, we can use the formula for cash breakeven which is given as:

$$\begin{aligned}
Q&=\dfrac{\text{FC}}{\text{P-v}}
\end{aligned}$$

Substituting the known values, we will get:

$$\begin{aligned}
9,600&=\dfrac{\$185,000}{P-\$23}
\end{aligned}$$

Cross multiply to remove the denominator

$$\begin{aligned}
9,600(P-\$23)&=\$185,000\\[10pt]
9,600P-\$220,800&=\$185,000
\end{aligned}$$

Next, we also need to solve for the depreciation. As we know, depreciation is used in solving for the accounting break-even point. The formula for this is:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Q}&=\dfrac{\text{FC + D}}{\text{P - v}}
\end{aligned}$$

Where, $D$ is the depreciation.

We also know that in order to get the financial break-even point, the NPV must be zero. Recall the formula for solving the NPV:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{NPV}&=-\text{Initial investment}+(\text{OCF}\times \text{annuity factor})
\end{aligned}$$

Since NPV=0, then we will have:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Initial investment}&=\text{OCF} \times \text{annuity factor}
\end{aligned}$$
